If
   T'(n) = 1 + T'(n - 2)
then
   T'(n - 2) = 1 + T'(n - 4)
so
   T'(n) = 1 + (1 + T'(n - 4))
which we continue to
   T'(n) = k + T'(n - 2k).

We know that
   T'(0) = 0
and
   T'(n - n) = T'(0)
therefore,
   2k = n
hence
   T'(n) = T'(n - 2k) = T'(n - n) = (1/2)n + T'(n - n) = (1/2)n + 0 = (1/2)n
thus
   T' is in big-O of (n)
where
   c = 1/2, x_0 = 0.
